	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=36476><span id= >perrish</span></a><br><span id=notbold>102 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.12]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>Fear can prevent thousands of points of damage for 100 mana, plus the 15 mana for snare.&nbsp;&nbsp;Are healers just opposed to that on principle?  <br><br>Twitching the cleric costs 200 mana to give them 60 mana, with which they can heal 199.5 hp if you figure that it pays for just over a quarter of a celestial heal.  That's a one-for-one ratio of heal to mana, actually a hair below.  Our own trickle heal combined with a lifetap has an efficiency that depends on the lifetap used.  Our healing powers are at their weakest at level 43, right before we get our new heals.  At level 42, the tap does 219 damage for 189 mana.  Transferring those 219 hp costs only 28 mana (rounding up, even though it's below 27.5) with the level 20 spell, for a total mana cost of 217 mana.  That's also a one-for-one ratio of heal to mana, actually a hair above, and you get to do low-resistability damage to the mob too.  <br><br>I often group with my brother's druid and his friend's shaman, outdoors of course with that set of toons, and other than chloro I'm the only one who has to do any healing.  We also have zero downtime, partly because no one has to spend any mana on anything but killing mobs.<br><br>Of course there are lots of places where the mobs will path into trouble, and then you don't use fear.  And there are times when you have multiple mobs and an enchanter high enough to keep them mezzed, so you let the tanks stay where the mezzed mobs are.  If a melee type is main damage source and is having hardware issues that prevent them from following the mob, they can ask me not to fear and I won't.  But never using it, so that you can spend more time sitting there waiting for a cleric to get mana back, just seems pointless.</p>&nbsp;<br>Necro 53 of Nighthaven<br>on Cazic-Thule</td></td></tr>
